sec.p:
Over the last 20 years a considerable amount of research has been carried out to identify the essential components of good design for dementia-specific facilities. Marshall (2001) reviewed the literature on designing dementia-specific facilities and listed a number of design features that need to be incorporated in a facility to provide quality accommodation for people living with dementia. The list included amongst other things the following features:


domestic and home-like;

scope for ordinary activities such as kitchen activities, hanging out washing, and garden sheds;

a safe outside space.

The new environment is specifically designed to increase the quality of life for residents living in its dementia-specific unit (Magnolia House). The project has three main objectives:


To improve the quality of life of the people with dementia living in Magnolia House;

To improve the caregiving experience of staff members;

To improve the visiting experience of family members, carers and loved ones.
